    summary: "The Russo-Georgian War (August 2008) was a five-day conflict triggered by Georgian President Saakashvili's attempt to retake the breakaway region of South Ossetia. Russia responded with a massive military intervention that routed Georgian forces, occupied parts of Georgia proper, and recognized the independence of South Ossetia and Abkhazia. The war was a watershed moment in post-Cold War European security.",
