    summary: "The Banana Wars (1898–1934) were what happened when the United States looked at the entire Caribbean basin and thought, 'what if we just... kept showing up with Marines?' Officially about protecting American lives and property. Unofficially about bananas, sugar, canal routes, and the deeply held conviction that small countries near you are basically yours. For thirty-six years, the US sent gunboats and leathernecks to a rotating cast of nations, toppled governments it didn't like, propped up governments it did, and left behind a trail of dictatorships that would haunt the hemisphere for generations. It was imperialism wearing a Hawaiian shirt — casual, persistent, and weirdly cheerful about the whole thing.",
